          "body": "The chapter holds together two commands that look contradictory. 14:13: *stand by and see*. 14:15: *go forward*. Both come from God within minutes of each other. The synthesis is not contradiction but sequence. First, Israel must abandon the project of self-deliverance — the panic in 14:10-12 is the panic of people still trying to control the outcome. Only when they have *stood still* and *seen* that salvation is the LORD's are they ready to *go forward* into the sea. The walking is not what saves them; the walking is the obedient response of those who have already received the salvation by faith. The order matters pastorally: anyone who tries to 'go forward' without first 'standing still' walks in their own strength and panics at the next obstacle."
