          "title": "The LORD gains glory in judgment",
          "body": "Three times the chapter states God's purpose in hardening Pharaoh and destroying his army: *I will be honored* (כָּבֵד, 14:4, 17, 18). This is not embarrassment-inducing divine vanity; it is the chapter's most important pastoral truth. The God of Scripture pursues His own glory above all things, and that pursuit is the basis of His saving acts. If God did not act for His own name's sake, His mercy would be arbitrary, unanchored, and revocable. Because He acts for His name, salvation rests on something more secure than human worthiness. Romans 9:17 cites this passage exactly: God raised Pharaoh up *that My name might be proclaimed throughout the whole earth*. The Egyptians' confession in 14:25 ('the LORD is fighting for them') and Rahab's confession a generation later (Joshua 2:10-11) prove the strategy worked."
